/a.deviantart.com/avatars/f/a/fallenangel77.gif height=50, width=50></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ***Best Style?***</span><hr size=1> I might as well add something, though it's probably been said in some way, shape or form somewhere else.<br>
<br>
Don't look to tutorials or websites to find out how you want to draw. As it was said, learn the basics first, and if you need help (as all budding artists do whether we know it or not), look for the tutorials that show that the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>creator knows what he/she is talking about</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, not whether or not he/she is a great artist. I've bought several books on drawing by artists that don't necessarily appeal to me (Anime Mania by Christopher Hart immediately comes to mind) but in READING the material I learned a lot about balancing my figures and poses among many other things.<br>
<br>
Another thing, I believe it's always best to use construction methods when doing your figures, but do a construction method that works for YOU, not the way someone else does it. Some like stick figures, others like ovals, others still like cylinders/cones/boxes, etc. I personally do wire frames. <p>Don't you wish life had an 'undo' command?<br>
<br>
